"# Chapter 13 — Memory: RAM, cache, disk, and why locality matters

A modern CPU can execute an ADD in about a third of a nanosecond. In
that same third of a nanosecond, light travels about 10 centimetres.

A modern DRAM chip takes about 100 nanoseconds to respond to a read.

That is a **three hundred to one** ratio. If your CPU has to wait for
DRAM every time it does an ADD, 299 out of 300 clock cycles are
wasted waiting.

So we don't do that. We put a small, fast memory very close to the CPU,
and try to keep the data the CPU needs there. That small fast memory
is called a **cache**, and understanding it is the difference between a
program that runs fast and a program that seems fast but is actually a
disgrace.

## The memory hierarchy

Every modern computer has a memory hierarchy that looks something like
this:

```
   Storage     Access time    Size            Cost per bit
   -------     -----------    ----            ------------
   Register    ~0.3 ns        ~256 bytes      most expensive
   L1 cache    ~1 ns          ~64 KB          very expensive
   L2 cache    ~4 ns          ~256 KB - 1 MB  expensive
   L3 cache    ~15 ns         ~4 - 32 MB      moderate
   DRAM        ~100 ns        ~8 - 64 GB      cheap
   SSD         ~50 us         ~256 GB - 4 TB  very cheap
   Disk        ~10 ms         ~1 TB - 10 TB   dirt cheap
   Tape/S3     ~seconds       ~unlimited      near-free per byte
```

Each level down is roughly 10× to 100× slower and 10× to 100× cheaper
per byte. Each level is bigger. The idea: **keep the data you use most
in the fast levels, and only reach down when you have to.**

That is the mechanical heart of a modern computer. It is why an
optimized program is a hundred times faster than a naive program that
computes the same answer.

## Two kinds of locality

The reason caches work is that programs exhibit two kinds of
**locality**:

- **Temporal locality:** if you used a byte just now, you are likely
  to use it again soon.
- **Spatial locality:** if you used a byte, you are likely to use the
  bytes near it soon.

Loops are the great example of temporal locality: the same
instruction bytes are executed thousands of times in a row. Arrays are
the great example of spatial locality: when you touch element 42, you
are probably going to touch elements 43, 44, 45 shortly.

Caches exploit both. When you request a byte, the cache fetches an
entire **cache line** — typically 64 bytes — into fast memory. That
handles spatial locality. The line stays in the cache until something
newer bumps it out. That handles temporal locality.

If your program has good locality, most of your memory accesses hit
the cache and the CPU never waits. If your program has bad locality
(random access all over a big array), you thrash the cache and pay
the DRAM cost every time.

## Cache-friendly vs. cache-hostile: a demo

Let us build two versions of the same computation. Both walk a
1000-element vector, sum all the elements. One walks in order. The
other walks in a scrambled order. Same math, wildly different speeds
on real hardware.

```
;; Prepare a big vector
(define big-vec (make-vector 1000000 1))       ;; a million ones

;; Cache-friendly: walk in order
(define (sum-in-order v)
  (let loop ((i 0) (total 0))
    (if (>= i (vector-length v))
        total
        (loop (+ i 1) (+ total (vector-ref v i))))))

;; Cache-hostile: walk in a scrambled order
(define (sum-scrambled v)
  (let* ((n (vector-length v))
         ;; step by a big prime so we jump wildly
         (step 65537))
    (let loop ((i 0) (count 0) (total 0))
      (if (>= count n)
          total
          (loop (modulo (+ i step) n)
                (+ count 1)
                (+ total (vector-ref v i)))))))

(sum-in-order   big-vec)   ;; => 1000000
(sum-scrambled  big-vec)   ;; => 1000000
```

Both return 1000000. Both do a million adds. But the second one
strides through memory in a way that thrashes the cache. On a modern
CPU, the second is easily 5× to 20× slower than the first, depending
on the cache size and the vector size.

The lesson: **the same algorithm, in terms of operation count, can
have very different real-world speeds because of memory access
patterns.**

## Why chapter 7's ripple-carry cared about width

Recall that our 4-bit adder in chapter 7 had a ripple time proportional
to the number of columns. Same shape here. Bigger data structures mean
more cache misses. A working set of 32 KB fits in L1 cache. A working
set of 32 MB does not.

Rule of thumb: keep hot data in the smallest structure that will hold
it. Don't waste bytes on padding you don't need. Use small integers
when small integers will do. That is not premature optimization; that
is just knowing where you are on the hierarchy.

## DRAM's dirty secret: refresh

DRAM cells store their bit as a tiny charge on a capacitor. The
capacitor leaks. Within a few milliseconds, the charge is gone and
the bit is lost.

So DRAM chips **refresh** themselves — every few milliseconds, every
row of the chip is read out and rewritten. This is invisible to
software, but it means DRAM chips have a duty cycle where they can't
be read while they are refreshing. It also means DRAM burns power
even when nothing is reading it.

SRAM (chapter 8) doesn't need refresh. Its cross-coupled NANDs hold
their state as long as they have power. That is why SRAM is used for
caches and DRAM for main memory: SRAM is faster and doesn't need
refresh, but it takes 6 transistors per bit vs. DRAM's 1 transistor +
1 capacitor. Trade-offs.

## The stack and the heap

Your program's memory divides into a few regions. Two of them matter
here:

- **Stack:** a region that grows and shrinks as functions get called
  and return. Every function call pushes a frame; every return pops
  one. Because access is always at the top, the stack has excellent
  spatial locality — the top of the stack is always in cache.
- **Heap:** a big region where variable-size objects live for as long
  as somebody has a reference to them. Access patterns are usually
  much worse than the stack. Cache locality depends on how the objects
  are laid out.

Motoi Scheme (like every Scheme) allocates `cons` cells, closures,
strings, and vectors on the heap. Local variables and the small stack
of active function calls live on the stack. Garbage collection
periodically reclaims unreachable heap memory.

Heap objects that are allocated together tend to be near each other in
memory, which helps locality. But over time, allocation and freeing
can fragment the heap, hurting locality. Copying garbage collectors
(which most modern Schemes use) compact the heap during collection,
which improves locality.

## Prefetching

A modern CPU also has a **prefetcher** — a small circuit that watches
memory accesses and, when it sees a sequential pattern, speculatively
requests the next line before the program asks for it. If it guesses
right, the next access is a cache hit even though it is a new line.

That is why `sum-in-order` above is so much faster than
`sum-scrambled`. The prefetcher sees the sequential pattern and gets
the next line ready before the loop asks for it. Random access defeats
the prefetcher entirely.

## Working sets

The **working set** of a program is the set of memory pages the
program touches within some short time window. If the working set fits
in L1 cache, the program runs at peak speed. If it fits in L2, it
runs a little slower. If it fits only in DRAM, it runs a lot slower.
If it spills to disk, the program is dead.

That last case has a name: **thrashing.** The virtual memory subsystem
of the OS pages memory in and out from disk, and if the working set
is bigger than RAM, every access misses and pages get swapped. Speed
falls off a cliff. Hundreds of thousands of times slower than in-cache.

Rule of thumb for a working programmer: know your working set. If
you can, keep it small.

## LLM training and inference — the same problem

Large language models are made of matrices. A modern LLM has hundreds
of billions of parameters, each a few bytes. That is hundreds of
gigabytes of data. It does not fit in cache. It does not fit in DRAM.
It barely fits in the whole rack of GPUs.

Training loops move enormous batches of tokens through these matrices.
Inference reads the whole model to produce a single next token. Both
are dominated by memory bandwidth, not compute. This is why LLM
serving is so expensive: you are not paying for the ALU. You are
paying for the memory bus.

Book of ML (chapter 16) builds a tiny LLM in Motoi Scheme. It runs on
your laptop precisely because the model is tiny — a few hundred
parameters. The math is the same as the big LLMs. The memory hierarchy
matters exactly the same way. Just at a smaller scale where the whole
model fits in L1.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

- Memory is a hierarchy, not a single flat thing.
- Programs run at the speed of their memory access pattern, not
  their operation count.
- Locality (both temporal and spatial) is what makes caches work.
- Sequential access is dramatically faster than random access on
  every real machine.
- If you understand the hierarchy, you know why some code is a
  hundred times faster than other code that computes the same
  answer.

## The loop appears

Every loop over a large data structure is where locality matters
most. A loop with good locality is a stream — the prefetcher keeps
up, the cache stays warm, the CPU never waits. A loop with bad
locality is a trap — every iteration pays a hundred-nanosecond DRAM
tax.

Chapter 12's CPU has a memory in it. Real CPUs have caches in front
of it. Chapter 14 goes up the abstraction ladder to assembly and
then to Scheme.

## Next

Chapter 14: assembly, then higher. From opcodes to Scheme.
